=========================================================
CONST POINTER IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
A Const Pointer is a pointer whose ADDRESS cannot be changed after
initialization.

The pointer is constant, but the data it points to can be modified.

Syntax:

int* const ptr = &x;

Read Right to Left:

ptr is a const pointer to int.

=========================================================
MEMORY REPRESENTATION
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

int* const ptr = &x;

        +------+
x ----> |  10  |
        +------+

ptr ----> x

Pointer is FIXED.

=========================================================
BASIC EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int main()
{
    int x = 10;
    int y = 20;

    int* const ptr = &x;

    *ptr = 100;      // OK

    // ptr = &y;     // ERROR
}

Output:

100

=========================================================
WHAT IS ALLOWED?
=========================================================

int x = 10;

int* const ptr = &x;

*ptr = 50;      // OK

Reason:
Data is not const.

=========================================================
WHAT IS NOT ALLOWED?
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

int* const ptr = &x;

ptr = &y;       // ERROR

Reason:
Pointer itself is const.

=========================================================
MEMORY DIAGRAM
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

int* const ptr = &x;

Before:

ptr ----> x

Attempt:

ptr = &y;

Compilation Error.

Pointer cannot point elsewhere.

=========================================================
CONST POINTER vs POINTER TO CONST
=========================================================

1. Const Pointer

int* const ptr;

Meaning:
Pointer constant.
Data modifiable.

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Pointer to Const

const int* ptr;

Meaning:
Pointer modifiable.
Data constant.

=========================================================
INTERVIEW TABLE
=========================================================

Declaration              Data     Pointer
------------------------------------------------
int* const ptr           Yes      No
const int* ptr           No       Yes
const int* const ptr     No       No

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 1
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

int* const ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;     // OK

ptr = &y;       // ERROR

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 2
=========================================================

int x = 10;
int y = 20;

const int* ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;     // ERROR

ptr = &y;       // OK

=========================================================
EXAMPLE 3
=========================================================

int x = 10;

const int* const ptr = &x;

*ptr = 100;      // ERROR
ptr = nullptr;   // ERROR

